  <div class="hero-eyebrow">Used Car Buying Guide</div>
  <h1>Buying a car on <span>Facebook Marketplace</span></h1>
  <p class="hero-sub">Don't pay dealer prices for private seller risk.</p>
</div>

<div class="article-wrap">

  <div class="intro">
    <p>Private sellers are a perfectly legitimate way to buy a car. You know exactly what you're getting into. No Consumer Rights Act, no 30-day right to reject — just you, the seller, and the car. Go in with a mechanic, take someone who knows what they're looking at, or be willing to absorb the risk. Price it in and you can pick up a genuine bargain.</p>
    <p>That's fine. Go in knowing what you're dealing with and it's an honest trade.</p>
    <p>Where it gets murkier is the growing number of sellers on Facebook Marketplace who look like a legitimate business — a logo, a trading name, thirty cars, five-star reviews — but haven't earned that level of trust and don't come with the protections that should go with it.</p>
    <p><strong>Don't drop your guard until you're sure which one you're dealing with.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <!-- Card machine test -->
  <div class="section-label">The tell</div>
  <div class="content-card">
    <h2>The card machine test</h2>
    <p>A real dealer takes cards. Not because they're generous — because they have to. Card processing is a standard cost of trading, and accepting it means accepting that your customer has Section 75 protection — the legal right to claim against their card provider if something goes wrong.</p>
    <p>A seller who won't take cards is telling you what kind of transaction this is. Whatever the Facebook page looks like, whatever the trading name says — if there's no card machine, there's no dealer. There's a private sale.</p>
    <p>Technically some protections apply to private sales — if a seller knowingly concealed a fault you may have a case. But you'd need to prove they knew, find them, and pursue a civil claim against someone who has your money and every reason to drag it out. In practice, you're largely on your own.</p>
    <p>That's not a reason to avoid private sellers. It's a reason to know which one you're dealing with before you hand anything over.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- The veneer -->
  <div class="section-label">The problem</div>
  <div class="content-card">
    <h2>The Facebook dealer who isn't one</h2>
    <p>Anyone can build a dealership on Facebook in an afternoon.</p>
    <p>A trading name. A logo. Stock photos of cars. Accumulated reviews — some genuine, some from friends, some purchased. A location. A cover photo that looks like a forecourt. It has the shape of a business. It does not have the substance of one.</p>

    <div class="scene">
      Search that trading name on Companies House. Nothing comes up.<br><br>
      Search the phone number. It appears under two other trading names on AutoTrader and Gumtree.<br><br>
      Search the address. It's a residential street in Wolverhampton.<br><br>
      Ask for a company registration number. They stop replying.
    </div>

    <p>The accountability you thought you were buying does not exist. If something goes wrong with the car — or if the car doesn't exist at all — there is nothing and nobody to pursue.</p>
    <p>Search Companies House before you engage. Legitimate dealers are registered businesses. They have a company number. Ask for it. A real business gives it without hesitation. No number means no registration means no accountability.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- The scams -->
  <div class="section-label">Specific risks</div>
  <div class="card-dark">
    <h2>The scams specific to Facebook Marketplace</h2>

    <div class="scam-item">
      <div class="scam-label">The car that doesn't exist</div>
      <div class="scam-text">A listing with professional photos and an attractive price. When you try to arrange a viewing, the excuses start. They're working away. The car is in storage. They can arrange delivery — they just need a deposit to hold it.<br><br>The car does not exist. <strong>Reverse image search every photo before you engage.</strong> Right-click any image and search on Google Images. If those photos appear elsewhere — on another listing, another seller's page, a manufacturer's website — the car in the photos is not the car being sold. Two minutes. Catches this every time.<br><br>You can also search the registration number on AutoTrader and other platforms. If the same car is listed elsewhere under a different seller or a different price, you've found something worth knowing.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="scam-item">
      <div class="scam-label">Moving you off the platform fast</div>
      <div class="scam-text">A genuine seller is happy to talk on Marketplace. A scammer wants you on WhatsApp before you've agreed anything — before you've seen the car, sometimes before you've asked a basic question.<br><br>Facebook can act against accounts reported on its own platform. Off platform, you're on your own. The conversation is harder to document. The trail disappears.<br><br><strong>If someone is pushing you to WhatsApp before you've established the basics, be very cautious.</strong></div>
    </div>

    <div class="scam-item">
      <div class="scam-label">The phone number that doesn't add up</div>
      <div class="scam-text">Paste the phone number into Google. Search it on AutoTrader, Gumtree, and Motors.<br><br>If the same number appears under two or three different trading names — you've found something important. <strong>Legitimate businesses don't need multiple identities.</strong> A number attached to "Midlands Car Centre" on Facebook and "Quality Autos Direct" on AutoTrader is a serious flag.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="scam-item">
      <div class="scam-label">The deposit pressure</div>
      <div class="scam-text">Other buyers are interested. Someone is coming this afternoon. Pay a deposit now or lose it.<br><br>Sometimes this is genuine. Often it isn't. A deposit paid under pressure to an unverified seller on an unaccountable platform is money you have almost no practical way of recovering.<br><br><strong>Never pay a deposit before viewing the car in person. Not for any reason, not under any pressure.</strong></div>
    </div>

    <div class="scam-item">
      <div class="scam-label">The distance purchase</div>
      <div class="scam-text">The car is three hours away. It can be delivered. You never see it in person.<br><br>Distance purchases aren't inherently fraudulent — but they remove every physical check that catches problems. And they make the pressure to just trust the listing that much greater.<br><br>For any distance purchase: get the registration, run the checks, ask for a live video call with the engine running. <strong>If they won't do a live video call, the car may not be what they say it is.</strong></div>
    </div>

    <div class="scam-item">
      <div class="scam-label">The phantom viewing</div>
      <div class="scam-text">A real car, but manufactured urgency. Someone's coming at 2, someone else at 4. If you want it you need to be there first.<br><br>Sometimes true. Often fabricated pressure designed to stop you thinking clearly or getting a mechanic involved. <strong>A car worth buying will still be worth buying tomorrow.</strong> A seller who won't give you time to do basic due diligence is not a seller you want to be rushed into trusting.</div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <!-- Before you travel -->
  <div class="section-label">Before you go anywhere</div>
  <div class="content-card">
    <h2>The basics — before you reply to anything</h2>
    <p>Get the registration number early. Run it on GOV.UK — make, model, colour, and age should match the listing exactly. Check the mileage at the last MOT against what the seller claims. If anything doesn't match, the listing is lying to you.</p>
    <p>Search the trading name on Companies House. Ask for the company registration number. If they're a dealer, they have one. If they won't give it — you have your answer.</p>
    <div class="warning">Never pay a deposit before viewing. Never bank transfer to an unverified seller. Pay by credit card — Section 75 gives you a route back to your money that bank transfer does not.</div>
  </div>

