  <!-- ClickMechanic -->
  <div class="section-label">Can't verify them?</div>
  <div class="content-card">
    <h2>Get a ClickMechanic</h2>
    <p>If the seller doesn't check out as a registered dealer — and you still want the car — the answer is a pre-purchase inspection.</p>
    <p>ClickMechanic sends a qualified mechanic to wherever the car is. They inspect it properly. You get a report. You know what you're buying before you commit to anything.</p>
    <p>It costs around £150 to £250. On any private purchase of significance, that is money well spent. A mechanic who has looked at the car properly can tell you more in an hour than any listing, any review, or any assurance from a seller who may or may not be traceable next week.</p>
    <p>A genuine private seller will welcome the inspection. They have nothing to hide. A seller who pushes back on a pre-purchase inspection — or who suddenly becomes less available when you suggest one — has just told you something important.</p>
    <p>That's your answer.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Short version -->
  <div class="short-version">
    <h2>The short version</h2>
    <p>Private sales are fine. Bargains are real. Go in eyes open, price the risk in, and get a mechanic if you can't verify who you're dealing with.</p>
    <p>What isn't fine is paying dealer prices — or assuming dealer protection — when the transaction is a private sale dressed up in a logo and a Facebook page.</p>
    <p><strong>Ask for the card machine. Search Companies House. If neither checks out — get the mechanic in before you hand over a penny.</strong></p>
  </div>

